Q.1. Who is the poet of the poetry “Ode on Solitude” ?
(a) William Wordsworth
(b) William Cowper
(c) Alexander Pope
(d) Puran Singh

Answer: (c) Alexander Pope
Explanation: Alexander Pope is the poet of “Ode on Solitude”. He was a famous poet and satirist of the early 18th century.

Q.2. Where does the happy man live, according to this poetry ?
(a) In forest
(b) In towns
(c) In his native land
(d) None of these

Answer: (c) In his native land
Explanation: The happy man lives in his native land and feels peaceful and satisfied there.

Q.3. How is he content ?
(a) To live peacefully
(b) to live with comfort
(c) To live with luxury
(d) None of these

Answer: (a) To live peacefully
Explanation: The happy man is satisfied because he lives a peaceful life, not a luxurious life.

Q.4. Who gives him bread ?
(a) Market
(b) Field
(c) Farmer
(d) None of these

Answer: (b) Field
Explanation: The field gives him bread, which means he grows his own food from his land.

Q.5. From where does he get his clothes ?
(a) From bamboos
(b) From leathers of animals
(c) From his flocks of sheep
(d) None of these

Answer: (c) From his flocks of sheep
Explanation: He gets wool from his sheep and makes clothes from it.

Q.6. How does the poet desire to sleep ?
(a) So long
(b) Soundly
(c) Sleep for less hours
(d) None of these

Answer: (b) Soundly
Explanation: The poet wants to sleep peacefully without worry.

Q.7. What does the Poet Wish ?
(a) His hours, days and year’s pass away softly
(b) To spend luxurious life
(c) To live with comfort
(d) None of these

Answer: (a) His hours, days and year’s pass away softly
Explanation: The poet wants his life to pass gently and peacefully.

Q.8. Meditation……………the happy man.
(a) Saddens
(b) Pleases
(c) Worries
(d) Disturbs

Answer: (b) Pleases
Explanation: Meditation makes the happy man calm and happy.

Q.9. The poet does not want anything to mark the place where he is
(a) Buried
(b) Sitting
(c) Hiding
(d) Lost

Answer: (a) Buried
Explanation: The poet wants a simple life and even after death he does not want a grand tombstone.

Q.10. A happy man’s wants are satisfied by the property inherited by him from his
(a) Uncle
(b) Mother
(c) Cousin
(d) Father

Answer: (d) Father
Explanation: The happy man is satisfied with the property inherited from his father.

Q.11. Hours, days and years slide away………………for the happy man.
(a) Hard
(b) Quickly
(c) Softly
(d) Tensely

Answer: (c) Softly
Explanation: His life passes smoothly and peacefully.

Q.12. Alexander Pope was one of the greatest…………………..of the early 18th century.
(a) dramatists
(b) novelists
(c) writers
(d) satirists

Answer: (d) satirists
Explanation: Alexander Pope was a famous satirist and poet of the early 18th century.

Q.13. The poet of‘The Rape of the Lock’is
(a) William Cowper
(b) Alexander Pope
(c) William de la Mare
(d) John Keats

Answer: (b) Alexander Pope
Explanation: “The Rape of the Lock” was written by Alexander Pope.

Q.14. ‘Essay on Criticism’is the famous work of
(a) John Keats
(b) Shakespeare
(c) Wordsworth
(d) Alexander Pope

Answer: (d) Alexander Pope
Explanation: “Essay on Criticism” is a famous literary work by Alexander Pope.

Q.15. A poem addressed to a person or thing or celebrating of an event
(a) Satire
(b) Ode
(c) Ballad
(d) Elegy

Answer: (b) Ode
Explanation: An Ode is a poem written to praise a person, thing, or event.

Q.16. ‘Loneliness’ is same in meaning as
(a) satire
(b) profound
(c) solitude
(d) mob

Answer: (c) solitude
Explanation: Solitude means loneliness or living alone peacefully.

Q.17. The happy man is content to live in his own
(a) tree
(b) town
(c) ground
(d) None

Answer: (c) ground
Explanation: He is happy living on his own land.

Q.18. What do you man by ‘slide soft away’?
(a) go away
(b) pass away smoothly
(c) pass away
(d) none of these

Answer: (b) pass away smoothly
Explanation: It means life passes gently and peacefully.

Q.19. What do the trees yield to a person in summer?
(a) wood
(b) fire
(c) fruit
(d) shade

Answer: (d) shade
Explanation: Trees give shade in summer which gives comfort.

Q.20. ‘Steal from the world, and not a stone’—here stone means………….
(a) piece of a rock
(b) a poluable
(c) a tomb stone
(d) a marble stone

Answer: (c) a tomb stone
Explanation: The poet does not want even a tombstone after his death.

Q.21. ‘W:ose herds with milk, whose fields with breaC, here ‘bread’ means.
(a) cake
(b) corn
(c) piece of bread
(d) any type of bread

Answer: (b) corn
Explanation: Bread here means corn or food grains.

Q.22. Whose flocks supply him with attire, here flock means.
(a) sheep
(b) cow
(c) dog
(d) elephant

Answer: (a) sheep
Explanation: Flock means a group of sheep.

Q.23. Alexander Pope was born in
(a) 1588
(b) 1688
(c) 1788
(d) 1678

Answer: (b) 1688
Explanation: Alexander Pope was born in 1688.

Q.24. Alexander Pope died in
(a) 1888
(b) 1848
(c) 1744
(d) 1724

Answer: (c) 1744
Explanation: Alexander Pope died in 1744.

Q.25. Who was one of the greatest poet-satirist and also a critic of the early 18th century?
(a) William Cowper
(b) William Wordsworth
(c) Alexander Pope
(d) Walter de la Mare

Answer: (c) Alexander Pope
Explanation: Alexander Pope was a great poet, satirist, and critic.

Q.26. How do hours days and years of a blessed man pass away?
(a) softly
(b) hardly
(c) coldly
(d) frankly

Answer: (a) softly
Explanation: The blessed man lives a peaceful life, so his time passes softly.
